It has layers for interoperability, commerce, communication, programmable and identity - all to make web3 invisible for the end user. Our primary focus is to make onboarding and adoption really seamless for your users.

Would love to connect and see if you can leverage this for engaging and retaining users!

Let me know if it piques your interest, would love to catch up with you guys!

Cheersü§ô

text:
Hi all! Passing on an announcement from libp2p team:

WebTransport is now enabled by default in Kubo (as of v0.18.0) and in go-libp2p. Current versions of js-libp2p (via the js-libp2p-webtransport module) also support it‚Ä¶ so this is ready to be played with!

üëâ Check out this demo where Alex used WebTransport to fetch a file from Kubo (go-libp2p) directly from the browser (js-libp2p):

Why this matters for users:

As you can see, this unlocks a new paradigm of use cases for applications building on libp2p like:

Enabling browser nodes (or light clients) as "full" peers in a decentralized network.
Uploading to Filecoin directly from the browser.
Getting data from the DHT by directly connecting to a DHT server node.
A little bit about the protocol ü§ì:

The state of WebTransport (more about the state of WebTransport here):

WebTransport is brand new and currently still in the specification phase (by the IETF and W3C).
Chrome already shipped support for one of the draft versions a few months back, and so did we. So libp2p is on the bleeding-edge! üßõ
Why it‚Äôs exciting for libp2p and why it‚Äôs better than old solutions (a lot more detail is available here):

WebTransport finally allows us to eliminate the need for a TLS certificate. This was one of the biggest hurdles to the use of WebSocket in libp2p.
Most libp2p nodes don‚Äôt have a valid TLS certificate (in fact, most of them don‚Äôt even have a domain name!)
Obtaining a certificate is hard to do in a decentralized manner. However, it‚Äôs a requirement for a browser node to connect with a WebSocket server, thus, we could never make WebSocket a default libp2p transport.
How does WebTransport do this you ask? üëá

Protocol internals (more on how WebTransport works here):

The WebTransport browser API now (finally!) allows us to accept self-signed certificates.
Instead of verifying the certificate chain, the browser will check that the SHA256 hash of the certificate matches the expected value. You‚Äôll notice that WebTransport multiaddresses contain (one or multiple) certificate hashes, for example: /ip4/

<hash>
Furthermore, WebTransport runs on top of QUIC and allows browsers to establish stream-multiplexed connections to servers. It‚Äôs a bit like the WebSocket protocol, but over QUIC instead of TCP (or rather: over HTTP/3 instead of HTTP/1.1).
If you‚Äôd like to dive deep, please check out our blog post announcing WebTransport:
Please let us know how it goes and what applications you‚Äôre planning to use WebTransport for. As always, you can reach out to us on IPFS Discord
-implementers
and we‚Äôll be happy to help!
